article.headline: Sparks drop second season opener in team history
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Storm gave coach Anne Donovan nothing
to complain about.

Betty Lennox scored 20 points, including 14 in the second half,
and the Storm tied a franchise high for points, defeating the Los
Angeles Sparks 93-67 Saturday night.

"Without a doubt, that's the best I've seen the team play,"
Donovan said. "I think tonight, you really saw us play to our
potential."

Lennox, who came to Seattle from the Cleveland Rockers in the
dispersal draft, sparked the Storm's 10-2 run early in the second
half. Later, she hit a 3-pointer with 12 minutes left to make it
57-44 and Seattle cruised from there.

"We just wanted to go out and play relaxed, but aggressive,"
Lennox said. "You have to have your 'A-game' against a team like
L.A."

The Storm (2-0) also scored 93 points last season against San
Antonio.

Lauren Jackson, the reigning WNBA MVP, had 16 points for Seattle
and Sheri Sam added 14.

Lisa Leslie scored 20 points for the Sparks (0-1), which dropped
only their second season opener in franchise history.

"It's a very tough way to start off," Sparks coach Michael
Cooper said. "Seattle had already played a game so they got one up
on us. We try our best in practice, but nothing prepares you like
an actual game."

Mwadi Mabika added 15 points and had four rebounds. Late in the
game, with the outcome all but settled, chippy play ensued and
Mabika was given a technical foul after arguing a foul call.

The blowout win for Seattle showcased the Storm's deep bench.
The reserves scored 28 points, led by Janell Burse with 12.

"Our depth and athleticism on the perimeter, were the issues we
wanted to address in the offseason," Donovan said, her team
shooting 53 percent. "I think our additions came through tonight.
We just showed everybody what we've known all along."

The win was Seattle's second largest against the Sparks. The
Storm defeated Los Angeles 92-56 on Aug. 6 in Seattle.

The Storm led at the half, 40-36, with Jackson getting 11
points.

Seattle controlled the boards too, outrebounding Los Angeles
31-23.
